50|$|The {{slippery}} hitch {{is effectively}} a <b>clove</b> <b>hitch</b> {{finished with a}} slipped loop. To tie one, begin as for a <b>clove</b> <b>hitch,</b> but instead of passing {{the end of the}} line through the loop in the final step, pass a bight instead, leaving the end on the original side. Pulling on this end will release the hitch. If tied in a gasket, this will quickly release the sail.|$|R
25|$|Complete with a half-hitch {{outside the}} loop, {{made in the}} same {{direction}} as the first two wraps, as for a <b>clove</b> <b>hitch.</b>|$|R
50|$|For example, when a <b>clove</b> <b>hitch</b> ties a boat to a pier, the end {{going to}} the boat is the {{standing}} end.|$|R
5000|$|A {{correctly}} tied two half <b>hitches</b> {{resembles a}} <b>clove</b> <b>hitch</b> tied around the standing {{end of the}} line, not a cow hitch.|$|R
5000|$|Finish {{with a half}} hitch, {{moving around}} the object in the same {{direction}} as the first turns, as for a <b>clove</b> <b>hitch.</b>|$|R
5000|$|Complete with a half-hitch {{outside the}} loop, {{made in the}} same {{direction}} as the first two wraps, as for a <b>clove</b> <b>hitch.</b>|$|R
5000|$|As {{long as the}} <b>clove</b> <b>hitch</b> {{can feed}} over the drum, the rope will feed through the device. In a fall, the drum is back driven by the rope as the device slides down the rope; when the drum {{rotation}} exceeds a certain angular velocity, it locks off to the frame {{and the increase in}} friction induced between the stationary drum and the rope causes the <b>clove</b> <b>hitch</b> to rapidly tighten around the locked drum to arrest the fall.|$|R
5000|$|<b>Clove</b> <b>hitch</b> is {{used when}} {{building}} an anchor using {{the rope and}} sometimes to make a climber safe quickly at a belay ledge ...|$|R
5000|$|<b>Clove</b> <b>hitch</b> for tying a rope to a pole - {{simple and}} won't jam, but not {{particularly}} secure and won't work on rectangular shapes ...|$|R
5000|$|This {{version is}} {{preferred}} when attaching a rope to pole or rod. [...] It is effectively a <b>clove</b> <b>hitch</b> {{with an extra}} initial turn.|$|R
50|$|The {{buntline}} hitch is a knot {{used for}} attaching a rope to an object. It is formed by passing the working end around an object, then making a <b>clove</b> <b>hitch</b> around the rope's standing part, taking care that the turns of the <b>clove</b> <b>hitch</b> progress towards the object rather than away from it. Secure and easily tied, the buntline hitch will jam when subjected to extreme loads. Given the knot's propensity to jam, {{it is often}} made in slipped form.|$|R
50|$|The lobster buoy hitch {{is similar}} to the {{buntline}} hitch, but made with a cow hitch around the standing part rather than a <b>clove</b> <b>hitch.</b>|$|R
